text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Expansion: Extent of internal discrimination%0a:Author: saraht%0a:Original: [[Articles.DiscriminationAgainstMandarinSpeakers|DiscriminationAgainstMandarinSpeakers]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.khushiw|khushiw]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 14:09%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210504-191938-279660#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 12:19-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210504-191938-279660#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI think Hong Kong-ers carry their discrimination over to the U.S., and apply it to any non-native accents when speaking Cantonese. My mom doesn't have an accent in English, but she also doesn't have an accent in Cantonese. This is surprising to a lot of Hong Kong natives because they hear her English and assume that she doesn't speak Mandarin or Cantonese. They'll find out she speaks Cantonese and then try to test it. They'll switch to Cantonese in the middle of their conversations, realize she has a native accent, and then become much friendlier towards her (not that they were hostile to her before, there was just a noticeable difference during/after their conversations).%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
